## Part 2: The Behavior Layer

Behavior trees (chapter 15) let creatures sense, decide, and act each frame. We'll give each species a `tick` function that runs its brain.

### The Bee's Brain

A bee wants nectar. It wanders until it sees a flower within 5 cells, then seeks it. When it arrives (within 1 cell), it \"feeds\" for 3 seconds (180 frames), then resumes wandering.

```scheme
(define (bee-brain eid frame)
  (let ((nectar (entity/get eid 'nectar))
        (behavior (entity/get eid 'behavior))
        (target (entity/get eid 'target))
        (feed-timer (entity/get-set! eid 'feed-timer 0)))
    
    (cond
      ;; If feeding, decrement timer
      ((> feed-timer 0)
       (entity/set! eid 'feed-timer (- feed-timer 1))
       (when (<= (entity/get eid 'feed-timer) 0)
         (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'wander)
         (entity/set! eid 'target #f)))
      
      ;; If wandering, look for flowers
      ((eq? behavior 'wander)
       (let ((nearest (world/nearest eid 'flower 8.0)))
         (if nearest
             (begin
               (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'seek)
               (entity/set! eid 'target nearest))
             (ai/wander eid 1.0 0.3))))
      
      ;; If seeking, check arrival
      ((eq? behavior 'seek)
       (if (and target (entity/alive? target))
           (let ((dist (entity/distance eid (entity/x target) (entity/y target))))
             (if (< dist 1.5)
                 ;; Arrived: start feeding
                 (begin
                   (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'feed)
                   (entity/set! eid 'feed-timer 180)
                   (entity/set! eid 'nectar (+ nectar 50)))
                 ;; Still traveling
                 (ai/seek eid (entity/x target) (entity/y target))))
           ;; Target lost: resume wander
           (begin
             (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'wander)
             (entity/set! eid 'target #f)))))))

(big-bang
  (on-tick (lambda (state frame)
             (world/step)
             (world/each (lambda (e)
                           (cond
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'flower)
                              (animate-flower e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'bee)
                              (bee-brain e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'dragonfly)
                              (animate-dragonfly e frame)))))
             state))
  (to-draw (lambda (state) #t)))
```

<!-- BUILD: wire as runnable example 16.6; needs world/nearest + entity/alive? in harness -->

[VISUAL: Bees now notice nearby flowers, steer toward them, hover at arrival, then resume wandering. Their paths curve naturally toward nectar.]

The brain is a `cond` over behavior state. `world/nearest` (chapter 13) finds the closest flower within 8 cells. `entity/get-set!` (chapter 8) retrieves a value with a default if unset—clean state initialization.

The bee now *values* nectar and *acts* on that value. This is utility AI (chapter 15) in its simplest form: a single drive.

---

### The Dragonfly's Brain

A predator values safety (patrol when alone) and hunger (chase when prey is near).

```scheme
(define (dragonfly-brain eid frame)
  (let ((behavior (entity/get eid 'behavior))
        (target (entity/get eid 'target))
        (hunger (entity/get-set! eid 'hunger 0)))
    
    ;; Hunger grows over time
    (entity/set! eid 'hunger (+ hunger 1))
    
    (cond
      ;; If patrolling and hungry, look for prey
      ((eq? behavior 'patrol)
       (animate-dragonfly eid frame)
       (when (> hunger 300)
         (let ((prey (world/nearest eid 'bee 12.0)))
           (when prey
             (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'chase)
             (entity/set! eid 'target prey)))))
      
      ;; If chasing, pursue and check capture
      ((eq? behavior 'chase)
       (if (and target (entity/alive? target))
           (let ((dist (entity/distance eid (entity/x target) (entity/y target))))
             (ai/pursue eid target)
             (when (< dist 1.0)
               ;; Captured: eat and return to patrol
               (entity/despawn! target)
               (entity/set! eid 'hunger 0)
               (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'patrol)
               (entity/set! eid 'target #f)))
           ;; Prey lost: return to patrol
           (begin
             (entity/set! eid 'behavior 'patrol)
             (entity/set! eid 'target #f)))))))

(big-bang
  (on-tick (lambda (state frame)
             (world/step)
             (world/each (lambda (e)
                           (cond
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'flower)
                              (animate-flower e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'bee)
                              (bee-brain e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'dragonfly)
                              (dragonfly-brain e frame)))))
             state))
  (to-draw (lambda (state) #t)))
```

<!-- BUILD: wire as runnable example 16.7; needs entity/despawn! in harness -->

[VISUAL: The dragonfly patrols calmly. After 5 seconds (300 frames), if a bee is within 12 cells, it breaks patrol and gives chase. On contact, the bee vanishes. The dragonfly resumes patrol.]

Now the garden has *stakes*. The bees feed. The dragonfly hunts. Population dynamics emerge: if the dragonfly is efficient, bees dwindle; if bees are wary (we could add a `flee` behavior when the dragonfly is near), they survive longer.

---

### Weather: Wind Shifts

The garden should feel *alive* environmentally. Wind changes direction and strength over time, affecting flower sway and—if we wanted—bee flight difficulty.

```scheme
(define (update-weather frame)
  (let* ((t (* frame 0.005))
         (wind-x (* 0.05 (dsin t)))
         (wind-y (* 0.02 (dcos (* t 0.7)))))
    (world/wind! wind-x wind-y)))

(big-bang
  (on-tick (lambda (state frame)
             (update-weather frame)
             (world/step)
             (world/each (lambda (e)
                           (cond
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'flower)
                              (animate-flower e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'bee)
                              (bee-brain e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'dragonfly)
                              (dragonfly-brain e frame)))))
             state))
  (to-draw (lambda (state) #t)))
```

<!-- BUILD: wire as runnable example 16.8 -->

[VISUAL: Flowers lean left, then right, as the wind oscillates. The breeze feels like breathing.]

Wind is now a deterministic oscillation. You could layer gusts (sudden impulses via `world/impulse!`) or make wind strength correlate with a day/night cycle (next).

---

### Time of Day

A `day-phase` that cycles through morning, noon, evening, night (0–1440 frames = 24 seconds at 60fps = 1 \"day\"). Lighting (paint-cell tint) and creature activity shift.

```scheme
(define (day-phase frame)
  (modulo frame 1440))

(define (sky-color phase)
  (cond
    ((< phase 360) '(0.3 0.4 0.6))   ; dawn
    ((< phase 720) '(0.5 0.7 1.0))   ; day
    ((< phase 1080) '(0.8 0.5 0.3))  ; dusk
    (else '(0.1 0.1 0.2))))          ; night

(define (draw-sky frame)
  (let ((c (sky-color (day-phase frame))))
    (let loop ((x 0))
      (when (< x 40)
        (let row ((y 0))
          (when (< y 2)
            (paint-cell x y c)
            (row (+ y 1))))
        (loop (+ x 1))))))

(big-bang
  (on-tick (lambda (state frame)
             (draw-sky frame)
             (update-weather frame)
             (world/step)
             (world/each (lambda (e)
                           (cond
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'flower)
                              (animate-flower e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'bee)
                              (bee-brain e frame))
                             ((eq? (entity/kind e) 'dragonfly)
                              (dragonfly-brain e frame)))))
             state))
  (to-draw (lambda (state) #t)))
```

<!-- BUILD: wire as runnable example 16.9 -->

[VISUAL: The top two rows of the canvas cycle through dawn blue, bright day cyan, sunset orange, and deep night indigo over 24 seconds.]

You could gate bee activity by day (sleep at night) or make the dragonfly more aggressive at dusk. These rules compose naturally—add a check in `bee-brain`: `(when (< (day-phase frame) 1080) ...)`.

